    slug: "assalato-wassalam-ala-rasool-allah",
    description: `Assalato Wassalam Ala Rasool Allah is an Urdu-language Islamic book dedicated entirely to the topic of sending blessings and salutations upon Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), a practice known in Arabic as salat ala an-Nabi and in Urdu as durood shareef. The title itself is a formulation of this very act of worship, translating to "May the prayers and peace of Allah be upon the Messenger of Allah." The book provides a thorough treatment of this important devotional practice, covering its theological basis in the Quran and hadith, its virtues and rewards, the various formulations that have been transmitted from the Prophet and the early Muslim community, and the scholarly discussions surrounding its proper practice and significance in a Muslim's daily life.

The book begins by establishing the Quranic foundation for sending salawat upon the Prophet, citing the verse in Surah Al-Ahzab where Allah commands the believers to send blessings upon the Prophet just as Allah and His angels do. The author then explores the hadith literature on this topic, including the well-known narration where the Prophet stated that whoever sends one blessing upon him, Allah sends ten blessings upon that person, elevates their status by ten degrees, and writes ten good deeds for them. Multiple hadith are cited to demonstrate the vast rewards associated with this practice, including the promise of the Prophet's intercession on the Day of Judgment for those who frequently send blessings upon him. The book presents a wide variety of durood formulations, ranging from the well-known Durood Ibrahim that is recited in every daily prayer to less commonly known formulations that have been transmitted through various chains of narration from the companions and the early generations of Muslims.

Each formulation of durood shareef is presented with its full Arabic text, Urdu translation, and transliteration for readers who may not be fully comfortable reading Arabic script. The book discusses the recommended times and situations for sending salawat, including during the five daily prayers, on Fridays, when hearing the Prophet's name mentioned, during times of difficulty, and when making dua. The author also addresses the scholarly understanding of what salat ala an-Nabi actually means — the theological implications of Allah "sending salat" upon the Prophet versus the believers doing so — drawing upon the explanations of classical scholars like Ibn al-Qayyim and Al-Qurtubi. Written in scholarly yet accessible Urdu, this book serves as both a reference work and a devotional guide for individuals who want to increase their practice of sending blessings upon the Prophet and develop a deeper connection with the Messenger of Allah through this spiritually powerful act of worship.`,
    metaDescription: "Assalato Wassalam Ala Rasool Allah is an Urdu guide to sending blessings on the Prophet. Covers durood formulations, virtues, and scholarly discussions."
