    slug: "astrophysics-and-the-holy-quran",
    description: `Astrophysics and The Holy Quran is an English-language book that examines the relationship between modern astrophysical discoveries and the scientific references found in the Quranic text. The book systematically explores how Quranic verses that mention celestial phenomena — including the creation of the heavens, the expanding universe, the orbits of planets and stars, the nature of black holes and dark matter, and the ultimate fate of the cosmos — align with the findings of contemporary astrophysics. The author approaches this subject from the perspective that the Quran is not a science textbook but a book of divine signs (ayat), and that the scientific accuracy of its cosmic descriptions serves as evidence of its divine origin for those who reflect upon its verses with knowledge and understanding.

The book is organized thematically, with each chapter addressing a specific area of astrophysics and presenting the relevant Quranic verses alongside the corresponding scientific explanations. Topics covered include the Big Bang theory and its correspondence with the Quranic description of the heaven and earth being joined together before being separated, the ongoing expansion of the universe as described in Surah Adh-Dhariyat, the classification of stars and their stages of development, the concept of a "smoke" state of the early universe mentioned in Surah Fussilat, the layered structure of the heavens referenced in multiple Quranic passages, and the description of iron being "sent down" to earth as discussed in Surah Al-Hadid. The author presents each scientific concept in language that is accessible to general readers while maintaining technical accuracy, drawing upon established astrophysical research and peer-reviewed scientific sources.

This book is intended for a diverse audience including Muslim scientists and academics who want to explore the intersection of faith and science, students of Islamic studies who need to understand the scientific dimensions of Quranic discourse, dawah practitioners who engage with scientifically-minded audiences, and general readers with an interest in cosmology and Islamic thought. The book carefully avoids the pitfall of forcing scientific interpretations onto Quranic verses that are better understood in their linguistic or rhetorical context, maintaining a balanced approach that respects both the established methodology of Quranic exegesis (tafsir) and the rigor of the scientific method. The English prose is clear and scholarly, with proper citations to both Quranic verses and scientific literature. The work contributes to the broader field of "scientific exegesis" (tafsir ilmi) by presenting well-researched correlations between cosmic science and Quranic revelation, inviting readers to marvel at how a text revealed over fourteen centuries ago contains descriptions of the universe that continue to resonate with the latest discoveries of modern astrophysics.`,
    metaDescription: "Astrophysics and The Holy Quran explores links between Quranic cosmic descriptions and modern astrophysics. English scholarly work on science and faith."
