    slug: "at-tawassal",
    description: `At Tawassal is an English-language Islamic book that examines the concept and practice of tawassal, which refers to seeking a means of nearness to Allah through various permissible intermediaries recognized in Islamic theology and jurisprudence. The topic of tawassal has been the subject of extensive scholarly discussion throughout Islamic history, with different schools of thought holding varying positions on the specific forms that tawassal can take and the boundaries that define what is permissible and what is not. This book provides a comprehensive treatment of the subject, presenting the evidences from the Quran, the authentic hadith, and the practice of the companions of the Prophet to establish a clear, well-referenced understanding of this important theological concept.

The book defines tawassal in its broadest Islamic sense and categorizes the different types that scholars have identified throughout the centuries. These include tawassal through the names and attributes of Allah, tawassal through righteous deeds, tawassal through the supplications of righteous individuals, and tawassal through the status and position of the prophets and the pious. For each category, the author presents the relevant scriptural evidences, explains the position of the major schools of Islamic jurisprudence, and addresses the common objections and misconceptions that surround the practice. The book pays particular attention to the distinction between permissible forms of tawassal — which are broadly accepted by the scholarly consensus of Ahl al-Sunnah wal-Jama'ah — and the specific practices that some scholars have considered controversial or impermissible, such as directly invoking the dead or seeking their assistance in matters that are within Allah's exclusive power.

Written in academic yet accessible English, At Tawassal is designed for readers who want to understand this theological topic in depth, including Islamic studies students, researchers, imams, and educated Muslims who encounter discussions about tawassal in their communities. The author maintains a balanced, evidence-based approach throughout, avoiding both the extreme of declaring all forms of tawassal to be shirk (polytheism) and the opposite extreme of endorsing practices that lack proper basis in the primary sources of Islam. The book includes extensive footnotes and references to classical scholarly works in Arabic, including the writings of Ibn Taymiyyah, Ibn al-Qayyim, Al-Shawkani, Al-Albani, and other prominent scholars who have contributed to the discussion. This makes At Tawassal a valuable reference work for anyone engaged in the scholarly study of Islamic theology (aqidah) and the jurisprudence of worship.`,
    metaDescription: "At Tawassal is an English scholarly examination of seeking nearness to Allah in Islam. Covers Quranic and hadith evidence, scholarly positions."
