    slug: "atlas-of-quran",
    description: `Atlas of Quran is a geographic and historical reference book that maps the locations, routes, and regions mentioned in the Holy Quran, providing readers with a spatial understanding of the events, places, and journeys described in the Quranic text. The Quran references numerous geographic locations across the Arabian Peninsula, the broader Middle East, Egypt, and surrounding regions — from the land of Makkah and Madinah where the Prophet received revelation, to the ancient lands of Egypt, Syria, Iraq, and Yemen associated with the stories of previous prophets. This atlas uses detailed maps, satellite imagery, and archaeological information to identify and illustrate each of these locations, helping readers connect the Quranic narrative to its physical geography.

The atlas covers a wide range of geographic references found throughout the Quran. It maps the routes of prophetic journeys, including the migration (Hijrah) of Prophet Muhammad from Makkah to Madinah, the journey of Prophet Musa (Moses) and the Children of Israel from Egypt through the Sinai Peninsula, the trade routes of the Quraysh mentioned in Surah Al-Quraish, and the locations associated with the people of Aad, Thamud, and the cities of Sodom and Gomorrah. For each location, the atlas provides the relevant Quranic verses, the scholarly opinions on the identification of the site, the current modern name and country where the site is located, and any archaeological evidence that supports or correlates with the Quranic description. Maps showing the Arabian Peninsula during the time of revelation help readers understand the political and geographic landscape in which Islam emerged, including the positions of major tribes, trade routes, and settlements.

The Atlas of Quran is printed with high-quality color maps that clearly distinguish between ancient and modern place names, topographical features, and suggested routes. The explanatory text is concise and informative, written in a style that serves both casual readers and those engaged in more serious Quranic study. The book is particularly valuable for Quran teachers who want to provide their students with visual context during lessons, for researchers studying the historical geography of the Quran, and for general readers who want to deepen their appreciation of the Quran by understanding the physical landscapes in which its narratives unfolded. By placing the Quranic text in its geographic context, the atlas helps readers visualize the journeys of the prophets, the scope of divine revelation, and the physical world that the Quran addresses, enhancing both understanding and reflection upon the book of Allah.`,
    metaDescription: "Atlas of Quran maps every geographic location and route mentioned in the Holy Quran. Color maps with archaeological context for Quranic study and teaching."
