    slug: "atlas-seerat-nabvi-pbuh",
    description: `Atlas Seerat Nabvi (PBUH) is an Urdu-language visual reference book that presents the prophetic biography (seerah) of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) through detailed maps, geographic illustrations, and annotated diagrams. This atlas provides Urdu-speaking readers with a spatial understanding of the major events of the Prophet's life, allowing them to visualize the geographic context in which Islam emerged and spread across the Arabian Peninsula. The maps trace the physical journey of the Prophet from his birth in Makkah through his prophethood, migration to Madinah, military campaigns, treaties, and the eventual return to Makkah for the Farewell Pilgrimage, giving readers a concrete sense of the distances, routes, and landscapes involved.

The atlas begins with maps of the Arabian Peninsula as it existed in the sixth and seventh centuries, showing the major tribal territories, trade routes, cities, and geographic features that formed the backdrop of the prophetic mission. Detailed maps of Makkah illustrate the layout of the city during the Prophet's time, including the Ka'bah, the hills of Safa and Marwa, the various districts, and the routes used by the Quraysh for their trade caravans to Syria and Yemen — the very caravans mentioned in the Quran in Surah Quraysh. The Hijrah (migration) is documented with route maps showing the Prophet's journey from Makkah to the Cave of Thawr, the path to Quba where he built the first mosque, and the entry into Madinah. Maps of Madinah show the original layout of the city at the time of the Prophet's arrival, the boundaries of the various tribal settlements, and the location of the Prophet's Mosque as it was initially constructed.

The military campaigns of the Prophet are mapped in detail, including the Battle of Badr with the positions of both armies, the Battle of Uhud with the mountain terrain that influenced the engagement, the Battle of the Trench (Khandaq) showing the defensive fortifications dug by the Muslims, and the various expeditions (sariyyah) sent to different parts of the Arabian Peninsula. The atlas also includes maps related to the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah, the Conquest of Makkah, the Battle of Hunain, the Siege of Ta'if, and the Farewell Pilgrimage. The accompanying Urdu text provides historical context for each map, identifies the key figures and tribes involved, and draws lessons from each event. This atlas is an essential companion for students studying seerah in Urdu, teachers at Islamic schools and madrasahs who use visual aids in their instruction, and general readers who want to deepen their understanding of the prophetic biography through the geographic lens that makes historical events more vivid and comprehensible.`,
